## I. The Memo as Origin Point

On August 23, 1971, Lewis F. Powell Jr. — a corporate attorney, a board member of Philip Morris, a former president of the American Bar Association, and a man who had spent his career in the White male social and corporate elite of Richmond, Virginia — mailed a confidential memorandum to his friend Eugene B. Sydnor Jr., chairman of the Education Committee of the U.S. Chamber of Commerce. The memo was titled “Attack on American Free Enterprise System.” It was eight pages long.

Two months later, on October 22, 1971, President Richard Nixon nominated Powell to the Supreme Court. The memo was not disclosed to the Senate during his confirmation proceedings. The secret report was dated August 23, 1971. Less than six months after delivering the document that would reshape American power for half a century, Powell was sworn in as an Associate Justice on January 7, 1972.

Powell’s argument was straightforward in its diagnosis and sweeping in its prescription. The American economic system, he wrote, was under broad attack — not merely from extremists of the left but from “perfectly respectable elements of society”: the college campus, the pulpit, the media, the intellectual and literary journals, the arts and sciences, and from politicians. He identified consumer advocate Ralph Nader as the chief antagonist of American business. Powell’s reaction was based in part on Nader’s 1965 exposé on General Motors, *Unsafe at Any Speed*, which put a focus on the auto industry putting profit ahead of safety and triggered the American consumer movement. Powell saw this as an undermining of the power of private business and a step toward socialism. His experiences as a corporate lawyer and a director on the board of Philip Morris from 1964 until his appointment to the Supreme Court made him a champion of the tobacco industry who railed against the growing scientific evidence linking smoking and cancer.

The turbulence of the 1960s was broadly distressing to America’s corporate elite. The civil rights movement disrupted Jim Crow across the South, drawing out and exposing to the nation the racist violence that had long enforced the social and legal norm of segregation and upsetting America’s all-White corporate suites and boardrooms. Anti-war protesters derided Dow Chemical Company’s manufacture of napalm and scorned the entire military-industrial complex. Women’s rights protesters challenged all-male corporate management structures. The environmental movement protested chemical leaks, toxic products, and the poisons belching from corporate smokestacks. Public health groups began linking the tobacco industry to deadly illnesses and lead paint companies to brain damage in children.

Environmental awareness and pressure on corporate polluters had reached a new peak in the months before the Powell memo was written. In January 1970, President Nixon signed the National Environmental Policy Act. Massive Earth Day events took place across the country. By early July, Nixon signed an executive order creating the Environmental Protection Agency. Tough new amendments to the Clean Air Act followed in December 1970. By April 1971, the EPA announced the first air pollution standards. Lead paint was soon regulated for the first time. DDT was banned for agricultural use in 1972.

The overall tone of Powell’s memo reflected a widespread sense of crisis among elites in the business and political communities. His opening declaration was stark: “No thoughtful person can question that the American economic system is under broad attack.” He identified threats coming from “the college campus, the pulpit, the media, the intellectual and literary journals, the arts and sciences, and from politicians.” He argued that the attacks were coming not just from a few “extremists of the left” but also — and most alarmingly — from “perfectly respectable elements of society,” including leading intellectuals, the media, and politicians.

Powell’s response was not a single campaign but an ecosystem — a multi-decade, multi-institutional project to capture the commanding heights of American public life. His strategic pillars were clear and specific:

**Capture universities.** Powell called for the creation of a permanent intellectual infrastructure: a “faculty of scholars” who could be deployed to campuses and against hostile academic voices. He urged the Chamber to fund scholars, speakers, and programs that championed free markets. He recognized that universities were, in his view, indoctrinating students with anti-capitalist ideas. He believed it vital to ensure that future generations understood that capitalism fueled innovation and opportunity.

**Reshape media narratives.** Powell advocated “constant surveillance” of national television networks, arguing that this applied “not merely to so-called educational programs (such as ‘Selling of the Pentagon’), but to the daily ‘news analysis’ which so often includes the most insidious type of criticism of the enterprise system.” He noted that “whether this criticism results from hostility or economic ignorance, the result is the gradual erosion of confidence in ‘business’ and free enterprise.” He urged the Chamber to insist on the right to be heard, on “equal time,” and to deploy “whatever degree of pressure — publicly and privately — may be necessary.” He emphasized that it was “especially important for the Chamber’s ‘faculty of scholars’ to publish,” noting that “one of the keys to the success of the liberal and leftist faculty members has been their passion for ‘publication’ and ‘lecturing.’”

**Pack the courts.** Powell identified the judiciary as “perhaps the most important instrument for social, economic, and political change.” He cited the ACLU as a liberal entity that had experience promoting the appointment of judges and wanted to see a similarly equipped conservative organization take up the cause on behalf of business. He wrote: “Under our constitutional system, especially with an activist-minded Supreme Court, the judiciary may be the most important instrument for social, economic, and political change.”

**Build permanent lobbying infrastructure.** In his section titled “The Neglected Political Arena,” Powell recommended using political influence to stem “the stampedes by politicians to support any legislation related to ‘consumerism’ or to the ‘environment.’” He placed the word “environment” in derogatory quotation marks. He wrote that political power “is necessary; it must be assiduously cultivated; and when necessary, it must be used aggressively and with determination — without embarrassment and without the reluctance which has been so characteristic of American business.” This would be “a long road,” Powell warned, “and not for the fainthearted.”

Powell recognized that “the entire program” required an active and aggressive media presence and the utmost care in brand management. He understood that long-term, lasting change required appealing to the hearts and minds of the public at large. He advised that all channels of communication had “to meet the most exacting standards of accuracy and professional excellence” so that the views they advocated would carry weight.

Powell emphasized the importance of strengthening institutions like the U.S. Chamber — which represented the interests of the broader business community, and therefore was key to creating a united front. He argued that “strength lies in organization, in careful long-range planning and implementation, in consistency of action over an indefinite period of years, in the scale of financing available only through joint effort, and in the political power available only through united action.”

The memo was delivered to a friend at the U.S. Chamber of Commerce. From there, it quietly began circulating among the country’s most powerful business leaders. Initially it was viewed and praised by only a select few within the Chamber. That changed on September 28 and 29, 1972, when the leaked document was the topic of negative treatment in syndicated newspaper columnist Jack Anderson’s Washington Merry-Go-Round. With quotations now public, the Chamber published it in full in its newsletter, *Washington Report*.

The implementation was immediate and systematic.

In March 1973, the Chamber of Commerce’s Public Affairs Committee convened a three-day conference at Disney World’s Polynesian Resort billed as the first gathering of the “Task Force on the Powell Memorandum.” The conference agenda mirrored the memo’s recommendations. Sessions focused on “enhancing the image of business,” strategies for political action, and creating a long-term framework to expand corporate influence — particularly how “the Chamber and business community can develop more political clout.” The task force divided into subcommittees, each focused on a core tenet of the memo: education, communications, political action, and judicial action. They were encouraged to think big, with instructions to “blue sky” their ideas beyond the Powell Memo’s already ambitious scope. They recognized that this was a long game, requiring not just money but sustained, strategic planning. By November 1974, the Committee on Business Overview — the permanent group born from the Powell Memo Task Force — had been hard at work for over a year, implementing the memo’s recommendations.

The results were staggering in scope and durability. What began as a response to perceived regulatory overreach became a blueprint for culture change that favored resistance to the federal government and long-term investment in changing the political direction of the country:

Within a decade of the memo’s release, the number of companies with public affairs offices in Washington increased from 100 to over 500. The number of companies with registered lobbyists rose from 175 to nearly 2,500. In 1971, there were only 176 companies in Washington, D.C. By 1980, there were 2,445 companies, 9,000 lobbyists, and 60,000 trade association employees.

The Heritage Foundation was established in 1973, funded initially by seed money from the Coors brewing family and Richard Mellon Scaife’s publishing enterprise. The Powell Memo precipitated an explosion in the growth of U.S. think tanks, and Heritage marked the birth of a new type of politically aggressive and openly ideological “expert” organization. The Cato Institute followed. The American Enterprise Institute was revitalized. Together with over eighty large non-profit organizations — funded by a gaggle of right-wing family foundations and wealthy individuals to the tune of $400 million a year — they formed what analyst Rob Stein called “the Big 80,” a conservative political movement that achieved a hammerlock on every aspect of federal government.

The Federalist Society, founded in 1982, began the systematic project of reshaping the federal judiciary. Powell himself had paved the doctrinal ground: his opinion in *First National Bank of Boston v. Bellotti* shifted the direction of First Amendment law by declaring that corporate financial influence of elections by independent expenditures should be protected with the same vigor as individual speech. This doctrinal seed grew, through decades of Federalist Society-cultivated judges and justices, into the Roberts Court’s decision in *Citizens United v. Federal Election Commission* — which broke radical new ground by striking down the edifice of campaign finance laws. The decades-long drive to rethink legal doctrines and ultimately strike down campaign finance laws continues apace.

The views of industry-sponsored groups — thirty-six of them documented in *Masks of Deception: Corporate Front Groups in America* — are regularly reported in the press as the views of citizen advocates. The sole reason for their existence is to convince the public that the corporate interest is the public interest and that labor, health, and the environment are “special” interests. The top funders of such groups include Dow Chemical, Exxon, Chevron USA, Mobil, DuPont, Ford, Philip Morris, Pfizer, Anheuser-Busch, Monsanto, Procter & Gamble, Phillips Petroleum, AT&T, and Arco.

By the close of the 1970s, the U.S. Chamber of Commerce had been transformed from a cautious, passive business group into a politically aggressive and ideologically driven machine, rebuilt to carry out the “careful long-range planning and implementation” Powell had urged. It became part of the broader vision he had imagined: an alliance of business interests and conservative political groups, united in opposition to the regulatory state and working together as a social movement for capitalism. Measured in money spent, the Chamber became the most powerful lobby in Washington — $770.6 million since 1998, over three times the amount spent by the next-largest spender, General Electric. The Chamber reinforced its lobbying power by becoming one of the largest conduits of election-related “independent expenditures,” spending over $32.8 million on federal elections in 2010. It sponsors the Institute for Legal Reform, which has spearheaded the campaign for tort “reform” — making it more difficult for average people who have been injured, assaulted, or harmed to sue the responsible corporations. Along with well over a dozen legal foundations, the Chamber has helped shape the powerful “business civil liberties” movement that has been a driving force behind *Citizens United* and other judicial actions that have handcuffed regulators and prevented Congress from putting common-sense checks on corporate power.

Charles Koch read the memo and concluded it didn’t go far enough. In a speech to the Institute for Humane Studies, which he had taken over in the early 1970s, Koch said the Powell memo didn’t go far enough because it did not urge specific restrictions on money being given to universities. He asserted that Powell was wrong in assuming that most businesses believe in “free enterprise” because Koch’s definition of that term was even narrower: he rejected the idea of equal opportunity laws and wage rules and health and safety laws, and framed them as inherently anti-capitalist, anti-free-market. He didn’t believe the business community was actually committed to free enterprise because it was willing to go along with common-sense regulations that the people wanted. Koch’s agenda has captured the Republican Party when it comes to business deregulation. As journalist Nancy MacLean documented, the campaign amounted to a sustained effort to “save capitalism from democracy — permanently.”

Lisa Graves, a researcher who studied the memo’s impact, stated: “This document was not a product of the democratic process, but it has had a profound impact on our process by pushing forward a structure for how corporations can exert more influence on American life. That came in response to a brief period in U.S.” history when regulatory and consumer protections were expanding.

As Jane Mayer and others documented, the strategy worked all too well: megacorporations now enjoy fewer regulations, lower taxes, more lobbyists, more businesspeople in power, and the ability to impede policy perceived as hurting their bottom line, whether that be related to climate protections or health care reform. A right-wing dark money network, financed over the decades by magnates from Bryce Harlow to Richard Mellon Scaife to Joseph Coors, funded think tanks, media outlets and writers, college programs, legal organizations, and politicians dedicated to advancing pro-business causes.

Powell later dismissed the memo as something he had written in his free time as a favor to a friend, claiming it had little impact. Yet its influence is undeniable. It played a key role in reshaping the balance of power in the United States, leaving a lasting impact on media, education, government policy, and most critically, the courts. The memo is both credited as having “changed America” and remains the single most requested document in the Lewis F. Powell Jr. Papers.

Senator Sheldon Whitehouse, in his “Scheme” series of Senate floor speeches, placed the memo at the origin of what he described as a long-running, right-wing scheme to capture the Supreme Court through dark money. The Alliance for Justice’s 1993 report *Justice for Sale* mentioned it prominently. The case for the memo being a seminal document in the neoconservative movement was made in John B. Judis’s 2000 book *The Paradox of American Democracy*. Because it signaled the beginning of a major shift in American business culture, political power, and law, the Powell memo essentially marks the beginning of the business community’s multi-decade collective takeover of the most important institutions of public opinion and democratic decision-making. At the very least, it is the first place where this broad agenda was compiled in one document.

More than 50 years after Powell’s memo, Project 2025 — a 900-page manual for transforming the executive branch, spearheaded by the Heritage Foundation, the same organization born from Powell’s vision — represents the culmination of his institutional capture strategy. The administrative state comprises thousands of civil servants who make daily decisions about regulations, enforcement, and policy implementation. Most Americans cannot name these agencies, yet they profoundly shape everyday life. Conservatives began viewing the administrative state as the true battlefield. The logic was simple: if laws cannot be repealed, defund or capture the agencies that enforce them. If legislation cannot pass, reinterpret existing laws through friendlier courts.

The critical throughline to surveillance: Powell’s strategy was about ensuring that corporate interests could operate with minimal government oversight. The result was a regulatory environment where corporations — including data brokers — could grow largely unchecked, while the state simultaneously gained access to the data those corporations harvested. Powell did not call for surveillance of citizens. He called for “constant surveillance” of media and textbooks — the institutional spaces where public opinion was formed. His project was to ensure that those spaces produced opinion favorable to corporate interests. The irony that would take fifty years to fully materialize is that the institutional architecture he built — the deregulated marketplace, the captured judiciary, the weakened regulatory agencies — would create the precise conditions under which a surveillance apparatus emerged that made his original project look quaint. Powell wanted to monitor television. His heirs built a system that monitors everyone, all the time, and sells the data to the government without a warrant.

The Powell Memo’s most consequential legacy is not any single institution it produced. It is the ecosystem — the flywheel of compounding institutional power. A Heritage Foundation policy paper becomes a Federalist Society legal brief becomes a Supreme Court opinion becomes a media talking point becomes a campaign contribution becomes a legislative outcome. Each component reinforces the others. Each year’s investment compounds into the next year’s capacity. The through-line is direct, documented, and unbroken.

